Service Principals (SPNs)
An SPN is essentially an identity for applications/services/scripts (non-interactive).
Created via App Registration in Entra ID.
Traditionally authenticated using client ID + client secret (or certificate) — like a username/password for apps.
Used for both:
External/third-party access (e.g., GitHub Actions, Azure DevOps pipelines, custom scripts).
Azure service-to-service access.

Access granted via RBAC (or app roles).
Downside: Secrets are user-managed → risk of leaks, rotation headaches, sprawl.

Managed Identities
Azure's solution to eliminate secrets for Azure-internal workloads.
Azure automatically creates and manages a special type of service principal behind the scenes.
No client secret visible or manageable by users — Azure handles rotation and lifecycle.
Two types:
System-assigned: Tied to a specific Azure resource (e.g., VM, App Service, Function) — turns on/off with the resource.
User-assigned: Standalone resource that can be attached to multiple Azure resources.

Ideal for service-to-service within Azure (e.g., VM accessing Key Vault or Storage).
Cannot be used directly from outside Azure.

